## Learn: Solving Absolute Value Equations

### Key Concept: Solving |ax + b| = c

For [c > 0], the equation [|ax + b| = c] is equivalent to [ax + b = c] or [ax + b = -c].

For [c = 0], the equation [|ax + b| = 0] is equivalent to [ax + b = 0].

For [c < 0], there is no solution because absolute value is always non-negative.

### Key Concept: Cases for Absolute Value

When solving equations with multiple absolute values, such as [|x - 3| = |2x + 1|], consider all combinations of positive and negative cases for each expression. With two absolute values, there are 4 combinations, but only 2 unique cases need be considered because if [A = B], then either [A = B] or [A = -B].

