## Example 2 — Real-World Absolute Value Equations

Solve each problem by writing and solving an absolute value equation.

### Step 1: Define the Situation

For problems involving tolerances, write an equation of the form [|measured - actual| = tolerance].

**9. WEATHER** A thermometer claims accuracy within 1.5 degrees of the actual temperature. If the thermometer reads 87.4°F, write and solve an absolute value equation to find the least and greatest possible temperature.

Let [T] represent the actual temperature in degrees Fahrenheit.

[|87.4 - T| = 1.5]

Solve: [87.4 - T = 1.5] or [87.4 - T = -1.5]

[T = 85.9] or [T = 88.9]

The least possible temperature is 85.9°F and the greatest is 88.9°F.

**10. OPINION POLLS** A poll shows Candidate Morrison will receive 51% of the votes with a margin of error of ±3%. Write and solve an absolute value equation to find the minimum and maximum percent of the vote.

Let [p] represent the actual percent of votes.

[|51 - p| = 3]

Solve: [51 - p = 3] or [51 - p = -3]

[p = 48] or [p = 54]

The candidate can expect between 48% and 54% of the vote.

## Example 3 — Solve Absolute Value Inequalities

Solve each inequality. Graph the solution set on a number line.

### Key Concept: Solving |ax + b| <= c and |ax + b| >= c

* [|ax + b| <= c] (where [c > 0]) is equivalent to [-c <= ax + b <= c], an "and" compound inequality.
* [|ax + b| >= c] is equivalent to [ax + b <= -c] or [ax + b >= c], an "or" compound inequality.
* [|<] and [>] strict inequalities do not include the boundary.

### Step 1: Isolate the Absolute Value

**11.** [|2x + 2| - 7 <= -5]

First add 7 to both sides: [|2x + 2| <= 2]

Then rewrite as: [-2 <= 2x + 2 <= 2]

Subtract 2: [-4 <= 2x <= 0]

Divide by 2: [-2 <= x <= 0]

**12.** [|x/2 - 5| + 2 > 10]

First subtract 2: [|x/2 - 5| > 8]

Rewrite as two cases: [x/2 - 5 > 8] or [x/2 - 5 < -8]

Solve each: [x/2 > 13] or [x/2 > -3]

Multiply by 2: [x > 26] or [x < -6]

**13.** [|3b + 5| <= -2]

No solution, because absolute value is always [>= 0] and cannot be [<= -2].

**14.** [|x| > x - 1]

Rewrite as: [x > x - 1] or [x < -(x - 1)]

Simplify: The first case is always true ([0 > -1]). The second gives [x < -x + 1], so [2x < 1], so [x < 0.5].

