## Example 4 — Real-World Absolute Value Inequalities

Solve each problem by writing and solving an absolute value inequality.

### Step 1: Write the Inequality

**19. RAINFALL** In 90% of the last 30 years, the rainfall at Shell Beach varied no more than 6.5 inches from its mean of 24 inches. Write and solve an absolute value inequality to describe the rainfall in the other 10% of the years.

Let [R] represent the rainfall in inches.

For the 10% outside the normal range: [|R - 24| > 6.5]

Solve: [R - 24 > 6.5] or [R - 24 < -6.5]

[R > 30.5] or [R < 17.5]

In the other 10% of years, rainfall was less than 17.5 inches or greater than 30.5 inches.

**20. MANUFACTURING** A soup can states a volume of 14.5 fluid ounces and must not vary by more than 0.08 ounces. Write and solve an absolute value inequality for acceptable volumes.

Let [V] represent the acceptable volume.

[|V - 14.5| <= 0.08]

Solve: [-0.08 <= V - 14.5 <= 0.08]

[14.42 <= V <= 14.58]

Acceptable volumes range from 14.42 to 14.58 fluid ounces.

